data.sampled:
It's a calendar spread with a twist because the amount of premium collected on the $90 put is less than the premium paid for the $105 call, but the $93 put makes up for the difference.

The calendar spread strategy is typically used to create a time spread by selling a near-term put or call option while simultaneously buying a further out-of-the-money option of the same type. The goal is to benefit from the faster time decay of the shorter-dated option while also maintaining some protection in case the stock moves against the investor. The twist in this case is the use of the $93 put to effectively lower the cost of the $105 call, resulting in a net credit instead of a net debit.
